### Assistant: The waffle cookie recipe looks like this,
Purpose:
To make delicious, buttery, sugar coated waffle cookies

Ingredients:
1 1/2 cup all-purpose flour (208 g)
1/2 teaspoon salt (2 g)
1 1/2 cup sugar (300 g)
1/2 cup (110 g) cold unsalted butter, cut into cubes
1 egg (50 g)
1 tablespoon vanilla extract (15 ml)
Waffle cookie iron
Powdered sugar, for dusting

Preparation:

Cream the butter and sugar together until light and fluffy using a stand mixer or an electric hand-mixer.
Add the egg and vanilla extract and continue mixing until well combined.
In a separate bowl, whisk together the flour and salt.
Add the flour mixture to the butter and sugar mixture and mix until just combined. The dough should be soft and sticky.
Chill the dough for about 30 minutes to firm it up a bit.
Preheat the waffle iron according to the manufacturer's instructions.
Using a tablespoon, portion the dough into even balls and roll them in sugar.
Cook the dough in the iron until golden brown. The length of time will depend on your iron. Mine took about 3-4 minutes.
Transfer the cookies to a wire rack to cool for a few minutes, then slide a metal spatula underneath them and transfer them to a plate or rack to continue cooling.
Repeat with the remaining dough, re-rolling the cookies in sugar between batches if needed.
Dust the cooled cookies with powdered sugar, if desired.

Baking Details:

Bake the pinwheels for 10-12 minutes.
Combine your dough for to 2 - 3 minutes to form dough. ...
Put your berries into the dough.
Flatten the dough in the middle.
Fold the sides over and pull the dough under as you lengthen the log.
Brush the loaf with melted butter.
Push the rock salt on top of the butter.
Bake at 350 degrees F (175 degrees C) for 35 to 45 minutes.

**Cooking Tips**

Remember to use a cookie sheet, or else the dough may melt right through the parchment paper!
The glossy look of the chocolate can be preserved by allowing the cakes to cool for a couple minutes before transferring them to a cooling rack
Place the pinwheels on a cooling rack and on the crystal glaze once it will firm them up, making them easier to stack or package.
Store the cookies in an airtight container for up to a week
